00:26:09,720 --> 00:26:18,000
♫  I'm hoping in the future, you'd still be tugging on the corner of my sleeves  ♫

305
00:26:18,000 --> 00:26:22,740
♫  I'm loving you  ♫

306
00:26:32,760 --> 00:26:35,460

307
00:26:35,460 --> 00:26:38,160

308
00:26:44,440 --> 00:26:48,440
You are going home with nothing anyway. Why are you in such a rush?

309
00:26:48,440 --> 00:26:53,960
If you had this kind of motivation earlier, you wouldn't only have a bachelor's degree at this point.

310
00:26:53,960 --> 00:26:55,940
Who is she talking about? Who only has a bachelor's degree?

311
00:26:55,940 --> 00:26:58,720
Doesn't Huaren screen resume?

312
00:26:58,720 --> 00:27:01,420
People with just a bachelor's degree can still interview?

313
00:27:01,420 --> 00:27:03,320
The job is not specially arranged just for certain people, is it?

314
00:27:03,320 --> 00:27:05,440
How unlucky!

315
00:27:06,060 --> 00:27:07,940
The initial interview starts now. Come in when I call your name.

316
00:27:07,940 --> 00:27:09,820
Li Yufang.

317
00:27:09,820 --> 00:27:11,560
Come with me.

318
00:27:17,320 --> 00:27:19,820

319
00:27:22,540 --> 00:27:25,000

320
00:27:29,320 --> 00:27:33,400

321
00:27:33,400 --> 00:27:37,020

322
00:27:41,500 --> 00:27:42,660

323
00:27:42,660 --> 00:27:45,780
Dear examiners and teachers, my name is Su Wei'an.

324
00:27:45,780 --> 00:27:48,020
I graduated from Huaren Medical University.

325
00:27:48,020 --> 00:27:50,420
I received the national scholarship for three consecutive years.

326
00:27:50,420 --> 00:27:52,900
I was the top student in my major for six consecutive years.

327
00:27:52,900 --> 00:27:54,980
Since you dropped out of school, why do you want to work in a lab as a research assistant again?

328
00:27:54,980 --> 00:27:59,680
Since you dropped out of school, why do you want to work in a lab as a research assistant again?

329
00:27:59,680 --> 00:28:03,648
Because my aunt and her two friends

330
00:28:03,648 --> 00:28:08,940
with Huntington's Disease participated in a drug trial, and they all had ruptured aneurysms.

331
00:28:08,940 --> 00:28:13,880
However, the drug company denied that these adverse events were caused by their drug.

332
00:28:13,880 --> 00:28:21,000
So, I want to find evidence to show them and prevent the remaining participants from encountering such dangerous events.

333
00:28:21,000 --> 00:28:26,020
You're that female student who asked questions at the neurology conference.

334
00:28:26,020 --> 00:28:31,060
I heard that you made Professor Wen from Zhang He Hospital embarrassed on the stage.

335
00:28:31,060 --> 00:28:33,180
I did ask several more questions.

336
00:28:33,180 --> 00:28:38,960
That's because I thought Professor Wen's explanation of the adverse events was unclear,

337
00:28:38,960 --> 00:28:44,600
and academic conferences are for exchanging ideas and discussions anyway.

338
00:28:44,600 --> 00:28:51,660
So, you wanted to use our department as a stepping stone to get justice for your aunt, right?

339
00:28:51,660 --> 00:28:56,600
No. I wanted to show them that research should be done properly.

340
00:28:56,600 --> 00:29:00,280
Even if my desire to get results is a hundred times stronger than theirs,

341
00:29:00,280 --> 00:29:05,520
I would never accomplish it by sacrificing safety and authenticity.

342
00:29:10,240 --> 00:29:13,640
Next time, when you confront famous professors from other hospitals,

343
00:29:13,640 --> 00:29:17,660
remember to bring solid evidence you've found.

344
00:29:18,500 --> 00:29:22,700
Did I pass the interview?

345
00:29:22,700 --> 00:29:29,020
Let's see if you can pass the second round of interviews.

346
00:29:29,020 --> 00:29:31,020
Thank you, Professor Wang!

347
00:29:32,380 --> 00:29:35,500

348
00:29:38,540 --> 00:29:41,080

349
00:29:52,780 --> 00:29:55,720
Didn't I ask you to wait at home?

350
00:29:55,720 --> 00:29:59,520
After all, I'm interviewing for your research team, and we should avoid any contact in public.

351
00:30:00,420 --> 00:30:03,700
I'm not afraid of that. You are the one that's afraid.

352
00:30:03,700 --> 00:30:06,380
I just wanted to be the first to confirm the good news.

353
00:30:06,380 --> 00:30:09,300
Looks like, you are sure of success.

354
00:30:09,300 --> 00:30:11,400
That's hard to say.

355
00:30:11,400 --> 00:30:17,480
I was fine with thinking on my feet, but you know my academic pedigree isn't an advantage.

356
00:30:18,260 --> 00:30:19,760
It's okay.

357
00:30:19,760 --> 00:30:23,880
Just prepare well for the second interview. The first one is just to get first impressions.

358
00:30:23,880 --> 00:30:27,700
The second one is what really matters. It tests your practical abilities.

359
00:30:27,700 --> 00:30:32,260
Is Professor Wang Huanzhong still the main interviewer for the second one?

360
00:30:33,420 --> 00:30:35,420
You'd better be careful.

361
00:30:35,420 --> 00:30:38,920
Professor Wang Huanzhong doesn't tolerate the slightest flaw.

362
00:30:38,920 --> 00:30:42,180
You can experience it for yourself

363
00:30:42,660 --> 00:30:44,220
his death stares during the interview.

364
00:30:44,220 --> 00:30:46,400
Death stares?

365
00:30:46,400 --> 00:30:48,260
Get in the car.

366
00:30:56,400 --> 00:30:58,100
Slippers, Jiang Jiang.

367
00:30:59,500 --> 00:31:02,100
Sorry, Jiang Jiang. It's a bit messy in my home.

368
00:31:02,100 --> 00:31:03,880
Flattie!

369
00:31:03,880 --> 00:31:07,260
No. Your place is better than I thought.

370
00:31:07,260 --> 00:31:09,140
Let me clean up a bit. You can sit down for a bit.

371
00:31:09,140 --> 00:31:10,860
All right.

372
00:31:15,140 --> 00:31:16,740
It's so awesome to live alone.

373
00:31:16,740 --> 00:31:19,560
You can do whatever you want. Put your clothes anywhere you like.

374
00:31:19,560 --> 00:31:22,540
If I did that, my parents would definitely scold me.

375
00:31:22,540 --> 00:31:24,780
You came out so late. Won't your parents be worried?

376
00:31:24,780 --> 00:31:28,260
No. I've talked to them about it.

377
00:31:31,720 --> 00:31:33,020
That's good.

378
00:31:33,020 --> 00:31:36,300
Are you not going to ask me what I said to them?

379
00:31:36,300 --> 00:31:37,980
What did you say?

380
00:31:37,980 --> 00:31:42,300
I said I already have a boyfriend now, and he will take good care of me.

381
00:31:42,300 --> 00:31:43,500
Of course.

382
00:31:43,500 --> 00:31:46,060
I will send you home no matter how late it gets.

383
00:31:50,260 --> 00:31:52,080
Fang Mingfan.

384
00:31:52,740 --> 00:31:58,820
Don't you think Dr. Gu and Wei'an's relationship has progressed in a rapid manner since they became official?

385
00:31:58,820 --> 00:32:00,780
We're both falling behind.

386
00:32:00,780 --> 00:32:04,020
Are you stressed about the progress of our relationship?

387
00:32:04,020 --> 00:32:06,380
It's not a competition.

388
00:32:06,380 --> 00:32:10,300
Your boss and Su Wei'an are moving in together. Are you still unhurried?

389
00:32:10,300 --> 00:32:14,500
It's their own business. Why should I rush?

390
00:32:19,740 --> 00:32:24,880
Fang Mingfan, you're so busy and come home so late every night.

391
00:32:24,880 --> 00:32:27,140
Flattie must feel lonely, right?

392
00:32:27,140 --> 00:32:29,120
Not at all.

393
00:32:29,120 --> 00:32:34,300
Cats are naturally solitary animals, and Flattie doesn't like it when we foolish humans cling to them.

394
00:32:34,300 --> 00:32:36,220
Am I right, Flattie?

395
00:32:37,220 --> 00:32:40,100
That won't do. Flattie needs people to take care of it.

396
00:32:40,100 --> 00:32:43,740
When you're not home, I can take care of it.

397
00:32:43,740 --> 00:32:45,140
- Really? 
 - Yes.

398
00:32:45,140 --> 00:32:48,800
That's great. I can give you my key.

399
00:32:48,800 --> 00:32:51,100
Remember to lock the door when you leave.

400
00:32:55,600 --> 00:32:58,020
What's wrong, Jiang Jiang?

401
00:32:58,020 --> 00:33:00,600
Fang Mingfan!

402
00:33:00,600 --> 00:33:02,840
You deserve to be single!

403
00:33:03,620 --> 00:33:07,100
Is it that my hints weren't clear enough, or is it because I'm not charming?

404
00:33:07,100 --> 00:33:09,000
I'm a girl, after all.

405
00:33:09,000 --> 00:33:12,140
When it comes to staying over,

406
00:33:12,140 --> 00:33:14,640
do you want me to be more direct with you?

407
00:33:14,640 --> 00:33:16,600
Stay over?

408
00:33:17,640 --> 00:33:19,680
You want to stay the night here?

409
00:33:21,380 --> 00:33:26,060
Wait, Jiang Jiang. I just think that your home is very nice.

410
00:33:26,060 --> 00:33:29,540
You would be suffering a grievance by staying over.

411
00:33:29,540 --> 00:33:34,680
Why would I be suffering a grievance? I won't feel that way, Fang Mingfan!

412
00:33:34,680 --> 00:33:39,620
I've always lived with my parents since I was little, and I commuted to college from home.

413
00:33:39,620 --> 00:33:43,620
I've never experienced the kind of alone time you have.

414
00:33:43,620 --> 00:33:46,860
Your place, even though not very big, is so carefree.

415
00:33:46,860 --> 00:33:49,620
Doing whatever you want every day, going to bed whenever you want,

416
00:33:49,620 --> 00:33:53,440
ordering takeout, and having late-night snacks, which sound like a blast!

417
00:33:53,440 --> 00:33:55,280
And the best part

418
00:33:57,200 --> 00:34:01,580
is being able to stay with you and Flattie.

419
00:34:01,580 --> 00:34:03,740
How wonderful!

420
00:34:04,500 --> 00:34:06,300
You really think so?

421
00:34:06,300 --> 00:34:07,900
Yes.

422
00:34:10,600 --> 00:34:12,240
All right.

423
00:34:25,120 --> 00:34:28,940
Do you know what the next step is?

424
00:34:30,240 --> 00:34:33,000
Subculture of nerve cells.

425
00:34:33,000 --> 00:34:35,120
My answer is the same as Su Wei'an's.

426
00:34:35,120 --> 00:34:39,220
Can you explain the digestion steps for the subculturing of glial cells?

427
00:34:39,220 --> 00:34:43,160
The digestion steps for the subculturing of glial cells require a 1:1 ratio.

428
00:34:43,160 --> 00:34:47,780
Add 0.125% trypsin and

429
00:34:51,320 --> 00:34:56,557
0.02% EDTA. It is advisable to cover the bottom of the bottle evenly.

430
00:34:57,600 --> 00:34:59,740
Do you have anything to add to her answer?

431
00:34:59,740 --> 00:35:04,600
Maintain a pH value of 7.5 and a temperature of 37 degrees Celsius.

432
00:35:05,920 --> 00:35:07,880
You may start.

433
00:36:32,460 --> 00:36:34,120
All right. Finished.

434
00:36:34,120 --> 00:36:36,360
Thanks, Director Wang.

435
00:36:50,000 --> 00:36:52,120
Does anyone else need to use this?

436
00:36:56,000 --> 00:36:57,700
No more.

437
00:37:06,760 --> 00:37:10,280
I've finished. I'll wait for you at the cafe by the hospital gate.

438
00:37:13,540 --> 00:37:17,160
Sneak attacking me? It's a little childish for your age.

439
00:37:17,160 --> 00:37:21,740
We're openly and honestly in a relationship, but you make it sound like we're having an affair.

440
00:37:21,740 --> 00:37:23,260
Because we're at the hospital.

441
00:37:23,260 --> 00:37:27,960
Last time, at the first interview, someone said that this position was set up for me.

442
00:37:27,960 --> 00:37:31,020
I don't want them to say you're favoring me for personal reasons.

443
00:37:31,020 --> 00:37:33,540
Personal reasons?

444
00:37:36,425 --> 00:37:38,105
All right.

445
00:37:38,700 --> 00:37:41,038
Su Wei'an, let me tell you,

446
00:37:41,038 --> 00:37:47,000
no matter what we do, those gossipmongers will always find something to gossip about.

447
00:37:47,000 --> 00:37:51,660
As for you, you should give me more chances to favor you a bit.

448
00:37:51,660 --> 00:37:54,500
No way. Guess what?

449
00:37:54,500 --> 00:37:59,080
I finally got to experience Professor Wang Huanzhong's "death stares" today.

450
00:38:00,140 --> 00:38:01,640
Huh?

451
00:38:02,840 --> 00:38:05,640
How did that happen? Did you make mistakes in your operations?

452
00:38:05,640 --> 00:38:08,924
No! At the end of the experiment,

453
00:38:08,924 --> 00:38:13,760
I turned off the UV lamp, and then he turned around and gave me a quick look. I was so startled.

454
00:38:13,760 --> 00:38:17,980
I asked if someone else needed it, but he said no.

455
00:38:17,980 --> 00:38:19,800
Wei'an...

456
00:38:19,800 --> 00:38:24,700
I mentioned Professor Wang's death stares to help you pay attention to his strictness.

457
00:38:24,700 --> 00:38:27,440
I didn't want you to be scared of him.

458
00:38:27,440 --> 00:38:28,880
Don't worry.

459
00:38:28,880 --> 00:38:31,660
Professor Wang looked at you, meaning he acknowledged you.

460
00:38:31,660 --> 00:38:33,360
Really?

461
00:38:39,000 --> 00:38:42,080
To celebrate you passing your second interview.

462
00:38:42,080 --> 00:38:43,400
More books?

463
00:38:43,400 --> 00:38:46,120
You passed the interview, and now you can read entertaining books.

464
00:38:46,120 --> 00:38:47,360
Aren't you happy?

465
00:38:47,360 --> 00:38:49,280
That's nonsense.

466
00:38:49,280 --> 00:38:52,900
I passed, yet I still have to read. Read by yourself!

467
00:38:58,200 --> 00:39:00,340

468
00:39:00,340 --> 00:39:04,660
 In the world of medicine, we have to face all sorts of possibilities.

469
00:39:04,660 --> 00:39:08,434
 We're attracted to this imperfect science

470
00:39:08,434 --> 00:39:13,120
 because the moment we're obsessed with bringing the dying back to life,

471
00:39:13,120 --> 00:39:18,460
 we grab every minute of each second of our knowledge and use our ability

472
00:39:18,460 --> 00:39:23,940
 to change a person's life's destiny and to make it better.

473
00:39:30,020 --> 00:39:34,100
 How old-fashioned! The libraries are even all electronic.

474
00:39:34,100 --> 00:39:37,260
 How is there a handwritten library card?

475
00:39:39,610 --> 00:39:42,130

476
00:39:42,130 --> 00:39:45,120

477
00:39:52,220 --> 00:39:55,060

478
00:40:00,030 --> 00:40:01,640

479
00:40:07,160 --> 00:40:09,780

480
00:40:13,120 --> 00:40:15,010

481
00:40:16,540 --> 00:40:21,340
You dropout student, full of useless information in your brain.

482
00:40:22,080 --> 00:40:25,640
You scare me. How come you walk so silently?

483
00:40:25,640 --> 00:40:29,860
You were acting so mysterious, I thought you were studying
some profound theory.

484
00:40:29,860 --> 00:40:32,290
Turns out you are doing this.

485
00:40:32,840 --> 00:40:36,300
I'm writing our names on the card. Is that illegal?

486
00:40:36,300 --> 00:40:39,740
No, but it's a waste of time.

487
00:40:39,740 --> 00:40:42,100
How is that a waste of time?

488
00:40:42,100 --> 00:40:47,440
This way, our names will be kept in the library forever.

489
00:40:54,700 --> 00:40:57,360

490
00:40:57,360 --> 00:41:02,240

491
00:41:03,580 --> 00:41:06,530
 Is Su Wei'an trying to cram knowledge?

492
00:41:06,530 --> 00:41:11,560
 Isn't it too late for her to study now?

493
00:41:12,740 --> 00:41:14,120
All right, you can go now.

494
00:41:14,120 --> 00:41:15,740
Thank you.

495
00:41:23,160 --> 00:41:25,160
Wait, Miss. Please don't put them back yet.

496
